qas.question: What is one of the most dangerous jobs for USAF personnel?
What does the abbreviation EOD stand for in the USAF?
What do some of these special missions in the USAF who deploy with the infantry do?
What are these enlisted positions in the USAF complimented by?
What other career fields have seen an increase in active combat missions?

answers.text: Air Force Office of Special Investigations

context: Beyond combat flight crew personnel, perhaps the most dangerous USAF jobs are <a1_0>Explosive Ordnance Disposal<a1_0/> (EOD), Combat rescue officer, Pararescue, Security Forces, Combat Control, Combat Weather, <a0_0>Tactical Air Control Party<a0_0/>, and AFOSI agents, who deploy with infantry and special operations units who disarm bombs, <a2_0>rescue downed or isolated personnel<a2_0/>, call in air strikes and set up landing zones in forward locations. Most of these are enlisted positions augmented by a smaller number of <a3_0>commissioned officers<a3_0/>. Other career fields that have seen increasing exposure to combat include civil engineers, vehicle operators, and <a4_0>Air Force Office of Special Investigations<a4_0/> (AFOSI) personnel.
